#compdef nomnomd
# =============================================================================
# nomnomd — Erik Agsjö's "Markdown with diagrams made easy"
#           — a TypeScript-Node CLI for rendering Markdown
#           documents with embedded nomnoml UML diagrams into
#           HTML output, with live-reload dev server, syntax-
#           highlighting via highlight.js, theme support,
#           emoji rendering, and recursive directory processing.
#           Distinguishing from mdbook, vitepress, hugo, jekyll,
#           and other Markdown-to-HTML tools by:
#             - nomnoml UML INTEGRATION — `nomnoml` is a
#               lightweight diagram DSL by Daniel Kallin
#               (similar to PlantUML / Mermaid but JavaScript-
#               native):
#                 [<frame>Decorator pattern|
#                   [+Component]
#                   [Component]<:-[+ConcreteComponent]
#                   [Component]<:-[+Decorator]
#                   [Decorator]o-[Component]
#                 ]
#               nomnomd extracts these blocks from Markdown
#               source and renders them inline as SVG diagrams
#             - LIVE-RELOAD DEV SERVER via --serve PORT —
#               serves HTML output + watches markdown files,
#               auto-reloading the browser on change
#             - SYNTAX HIGHLIGHTING via highlight.js — code
#               blocks get language-aware coloring; --hltheme
#               chooses from highlight.js's 200+ built-in
#               themes (atom-one-dark / github-dark / nord /
#               solarized-light / etc.)
#             - CUSTOM THEMES via --theme FILE — provide CSS
#               file for layout / typography / colors
#             - RECURSIVE PROCESSING via -r / --recursive —
#               walks directory tree, processes all .md files
#               preserving structure in output directory
#             - FRONT-MATTER PARSING via markdown-it-front-
#               matter — YAML metadata blocks at top of each
#               file extracted into page metadata
#             - EMOJI RENDERING via markdown-it-emoji —
#               `:smile:` / `:rocket:` / etc. converted to
#               Unicode or twemoji
#             - DIR-LISTING GENERATION — `dirlisting.ts`
#               auto-generates index pages for directories
#             - INCLUDE DIRECTIVE — `{{include otherfile.md}}`
#               syntax inlines other files (markdown-it-fence
#               extension)
#             - LINK REWRITING — relative markdown links
#               (`./other.md`) rewritten to .html targets
#               for browsing the built site
#             - STATIC ASSET COPYING — non-markdown files (CSS,
#               images, JS) copied verbatim to output dir
#             - HTML WRAPPING — content wrapped in templated
#               HTML shell with reload script (dev mode) +
#               unzoom script (mobile-friendly viewport)
#             - arg PACKAGE for CLI parsing — Vercel's
#               `arg` package (minimal Node argv parser);
#               not yargs or commander
#           Used by: technical writers wanting Markdown +
#           UML in one tool, software architects documenting
#           system designs with both prose and diagrams, and
#           as a reference implementation of markdown-it +
#           markdown-it-front-matter + markdown-it-emoji +
#           highlight.js + nomnoml + arg composition in
#           TypeScript-Node.
#
# Author:  Erik Agsjö (erkkah on GitHub) — Swedish independent
#          developer.  Maintains nomnomd, alongside other
#          Node.js + Go tooling.  License: MIT.
# Source:  https://github.com/erkkah/nomnomd
#          https://github.com/erkkah/nomnomd/blob/master/src/index.ts
#          https://github.com/erkkah/nomnomd/blob/master/package.json
# CLI:     src/index.ts — uses Vercel's `arg` package (minimal
#          Node argv parser).  Headline library: **markdown-it**
#          (markdown-it is the new variant being documented here,
#          completing Axis 19 three-language symmetry across
#          Rust / Go / TS-Node).
# Library: markdown-it (https://github.com/markdown-it/markdown-it
#          — "Markdown parser, done right. 100% CommonMark
#           support, extensions, syntax plugins & high speed"
#           — Vitaly Puzrin (puzrin) + Alex Kocharin
#           (rlidwka) under the nodeca / markdown-it org.
#           Distinct from pulldown-cmark (R665, Rust Axis 19
#           opener), yuin/goldmark (R666, Go Axis 19
#           expansion), marked (Christopher Jeffrey's older
#           Node Markdown lib), and remark (Titus Wormer's
#           AST-based Node Markdown lib) by being:
#              1. CommonMark 0.30 COMPLIANT — markdown-it
#                 passes the full CommonMark conformance suite.
#                 The "100% CommonMark support" claim has been
#                 a marketing differentiator since 2014 when
#                 markdown-it was created (markdown.pl,
#                 PHP-markdown, and original marked were not
#                 CommonMark-compliant at the time).
#              2. PLUGIN ECOSYSTEM — markdown-it's central
#                 design is the .use(plugin) API:
#                   import markdownit from 'markdown-it';
#                   import emoji from 'markdown-it-emoji';
#                   import footnote from 'markdown-it-footnote';
#                   import frontMatter from 'markdown-it-front-matter';
#                   const md = markdownit('commonmark')
#                     .use(emoji)
#                     .use(footnote)
#                     .use(frontMatter, console.log);
#                   md.render('# Hello :smile:');
#                 Over 400 markdown-it-* plugins published on
#                 npm — emoji, footnote, anchor, attrs,
#                 highlightjs, katex, mathjax, mark, sub, sup,
#                 ins, del, container, deflist, abbr, image-
#                 figures, table-of-contents, prism, table,
#                 wikilinks, headers, etc.  Distinct from
#                 pulldown-cmark's Options-bitflags model and
#                 goldmark's Extender interface.
#              3. RULE-BASED ARCHITECTURE — internal parsing
#                 follows a rule pipeline (core + block + inline
#                 rules); plugins can insert / replace / disable
#                 individual rules:
#                   md.core.ruler.before('normalize', 'my-rule', fn)
#                   md.block.ruler.disable('hr')
#                   md.inline.ruler.replace('emphasis', fn)
#                 More flexible than goldmark's Extender (which
#                 requires implementing multiple interfaces).
#              4. HIGH-PERFORMANCE — markdown-it benchmarks
#                 ~10x faster than marked in some scenarios;
#                 not as fast as pulldown-cmark (Rust) but
#                 fastest among pure-JS Markdown libraries.
#                 Token-based intermediate representation
#                 reduces allocation overhead.
#              5. PRESETS — markdownit('commonmark'),
#                 markdownit('default'), markdownit('zero')
#                 provide pre-configured rule sets;
#                 'commonmark' = strict spec, 'default' = GFM-
#                 friendly extras enabled, 'zero' = no rules
#                 (start from scratch).
#              6. HTML SAFE BY DEFAULT — html option = false
#                 (default) escapes inline HTML; html=true
#                 allows raw HTML for trusted input.
#              7. LINKIFY + TYPOGRAPHER + BREAKS options —
#                 - linkify: autolink URLs
#                 - typographer: smart quotes, em/en dashes
#                 - breaks: convert newlines to <br>
#                 Each toggleable independently.
#              8. STREAMING-FRIENDLY TOKEN ARRAY — md.parse()
#                 returns a flat array of Token objects; not
#                 an AST tree.  Plugins manipulate the token
#                 stream.  Distinct from remark (mdast AST)
#                 and goldmark (AST nodes).
#              9. ZERO RUNTIME DEPENDENCIES (almost) —
#                 markdown-it 14 has only 4 production deps
#                 (argparse, entities, linkify-it, mdurl,
#                 punycode.js, uc.micro); essentially pure
#                 implementation.
#             10. VITALY-PUZRIN / NODECA / markdown-it-ORG
#                 ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE — Vitaly Puzrin (Russian
#                 developer) + Alex Kocharin maintain
#                 markdown-it under the nodeca / markdown-it
#                 GitHub organization.  Vitaly also maintains:
#                   * markdown-it       — Markdown parser    (THIS)
#                   * js-yaml           — YAML parser
#                   * pako              — zlib in JS
#                   * embedded-graphics — for STM32 micros
#                   * fontello          — icon-font generator
#                   * remarkable        — original markdown-it
#                                          predecessor (now
#                                          deprecated; markdown-it
#                                          is the canonical
#                                          replacement)
#                 Distinct from Sean McArthur (Hyperium), Tolnay
#                 (serde), Sorhus (Node CLI utils), Titus Wormer
#                 (remark/unified ecosystem), Christopher
#                 Jeffrey (marked).)
# License: MIT (markdown-it); MIT (nomnomd)
# Status:  markdown-it — 21,506+ stars on markdown-it/markdown-it,
#          ~80M weekly npm downloads (TOP-30 npm package by
#          downloads); foundational Markdown library used by:
#            * VuePress (Vue docs)
#            * VitePress (Vue docs, successor)
#            * Discord.js (some embed rendering)
#            * Atom editor (Markdown preview)
#            * VS Code (Markdown preview extension)
#            * Eleventy (11ty, markdown-it preset)
#            * Joplin (note-taking app)
#            * Slidev (developer presentation tool)
#            * mathpix-markdown-it (LaTeX-extended Markdown)
#            * markdownlint (via lint rules)
#            * mkdocs-material (some plugins)
#            * nomnomd (THIS)
#            * 50,000+ npm packages
#          nomnomd — 2+ stars on erkkah/nomnomd, used by
#          authors wanting Markdown + nomnoml UML diagrams
#          in one tool.
